responses.text:
Below is a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates the scenario you described: a simple dashboard where widgets can be added and removed dynamically. It includes two side-by-side implementations:

- "Leaking version" — intentionally buggy: when a widget is removed we keep DOM references and attached event listeners (via closures) that are never cleared. The result is that the page's visible DOM shrinks but JavaScript-held references keep the widget data and DOM nodes alive, causing memory to grow.
- "Fixed version" — properly removes event listeners and clears references so removed widgets can be garbage-collected.
- A live widget-count tracker shows the number of active widgets for each side and a simple retained-nodes count (estimated by counting references kept in JS arrays). There is also a short explanation below the demo explaining why claiming "garbage collector isn't working" is usually incorrect.

Save the entire text below as a file like dashboard-memory-demo.html and open it in a modern browser.

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>Widget Dashboard: Leaking vs Fixed (GC demo)</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" />
  <style>
    body { font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", Roboto, Arial; margin: 20px; color:#111 }
    h1 { margin: 0 0 12px 0; font-size: 20px }
    .container { display: flex; gap: 20px; align-items: flex-start }
    .panel { border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; width: 48%; box-shadow: 0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.03) }
    .controls { margin-bottom: 8px; display:flex; gap:8px; align-items:center }
    button { padding: 6px 10px; border-radius:4px; border:1px solid #bbb; background:#fafafa; cursor:pointer }
    button:active { transform: translateY(1px) }
    .widgets { border-top:1px dashed #eee; margin-top:8px; padding-top:8px; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:8px }
    .widget { background:linear-gradient(180deg,#fff,#f7f7ff); padding:8px; border-radius:6px; border:1px solid #e2e2f0; width: 180px; box-sizing:border-box; box-shadow:0 1px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.03)}
    .widget h4 { margin: 0 0 6px 0; font-size:13px }
    .widget p { margin:0; font-size:12px; color:#333 }
    .tracker { margin-top:10px; font-size:13px }
    .muted { color:#666; font-size:13px; margin-top:10px }
    pre { background:#f6f6f6; padding:8px; border-radius:6px; overflow:auto }
    .explain { margin-top:12px; font-size:14px; line-height:1.4 }
    .bad { color:#9b1c1c; font-weight:600 }
    .good { color:#0a6b0a; font-weight:600 }
    .stats { display:flex; gap:8px; margin-top:6px; align-items:center }
    .stat { padding:6px 8px; background:#fff; border:1px solid #eee; border-radius:6px; font-size:13px }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Widget Dashboard — "Leaking" vs Fixed (demo)</h1>
  <p class="muted">Add/remove widgets on each side. The left panel contains an intentionally-buggy implementation that keeps JS references & event closures after widget removal. The right panel cleans up properly. Below is a simple tracker that shows how many widget objects are still retained by JavaScript.</p>

  <div class="container">
    <div class="panel" id="leftPanel">
      <h2 style="margin:0 0 8px 0">Leaking version <span class="bad">(buggy)</span></h2>
      <div class="controls">
        <button id="leftAdd">Add widget</button>
        <button id="leftRemove">Remove widget</button>
        <div class="stats">
          <div class="stat">Visible widgets: <span id="leftVisible">0</span></div>
          <div class="stat">Retained references: <span id="leftRetained">0</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="widgets" id="leftWidgets"></div>
      <div class="muted">Note: removed widgets remain referenced by internal structures.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="panel" id="rightPanel">
      <h2 style="margin:0 0 8px 0">Fixed version <span class="good">(cleans up)</span></h2>
      <div class="controls">
        <button id="rightAdd">Add widget</button>
        <button id="rightRemove">Remove widget</button>
        <div class="stats">
          <div class="stat">Visible widgets: <span id="rightVisible">0</span></div>
          <div class="stat">Retained references: <span id="rightRetained">0</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="widgets" id="rightWidgets"></div>
      <div class="muted">Removed widgets have their listeners detached and references cleared.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top:16px" class="explain">
    <strong>Explanation (short):</strong>
    <div style="margin-top:6px">
      If removed widgets appear to release from the DOM but memory (as shown by a dashboard or devtools heap) grows, it typically means something in your JS code is still holding references to those widgets (event listeners, arrays, maps, timers, closures). The garbage collector works when there are no reachable references to an object. This demo shows a common mistake: keeping arrays of widget objects or closures that close over DOM nodes without clearing them when the widget is removed — this prevents GC, so memory appears to "grow" even if DOM nodes are gone.
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    (function () {
      // Utility: create a widget DOM node with a button and some retained data
      function createWidgetElement(id, onClick) {
        var el = document.createElement('div');
        el.className = 'widget';
        var h = document.createElement('h4');
        h.textContent = 'Widget #' + id;
        var p = document.createElement('p');
        p.textContent = 'Some stateful content';
        var btn = document.createElement('button');
        btn.textContent = 'Action';
        btn.style.marginTop = '8px';
        btn.onclick = onClick;
        el.appendChild(h);
        el.appendChild(p);
        el.appendChild(btn);
        return el;
      }

      // ---------------------------
      // Leaking implementation
      // ---------------------------
      var leftNextId = 1;
      var leftVisibleContainer = document.getElementById('leftWidgets');
      var leftVisibleCounter = document.getElementById('leftVisible');
      var leftRetainedCounter = document.getElementById('leftRetained');

      // This array intentionally keeps references to removed widgets -> memory leak
      var leftRetained = [];

      function leftAddWidget() {
        var id = leftNextId++;
        // A piece of data that simulates heavier retained memory (string repeated)
        var heavyString = new Array(2000).join('x') + id; // ~2KB-ish per widget
        // create DOM element for the widget
        var el = createWidgetElement(id, function onAction() {
          // closure captures el and heavyString -> keeps them reachable if onAction remains referenced
          console.log('Left Widget action', id, el ? el.tagName : null);
        });

        // Put DOM into visible area
        leftVisibleContainer.appendChild(el);
        updateLeftVisibleCount();

        // BUG: we push an object that references both the DOM element and the closure.
        // Even after we remove el from the DOM, this array still holds references => can't GC.
        leftRetained.push({
          id: id,
          nodeRef: el,
          heavy: heavyString,
          action: el.querySelector('button').onclick
        });

        updateLeftRetainedCount();
      }

      function leftRemoveWidget() {
        // remove last visible one from DOM
        var nodes = leftVisibleContainer.children;
        if (!nodes.length) return;
        var last = nodes[nodes.length - 1];
        leftVisibleContainer.removeChild(last);
        updateLeftVisibleCount();
        // Note: we intentionally do NOT remove references from leftRetained.
        // So although DOM node is removed, JS still holds references in leftRetained.
        // This simulates a dashboard that keeps inactive widgets in an array for "undo"
      }

      function updateLeftVisibleCount() {
        leftVisibleCounter.textContent = leftVisibleContainer.children.length;
      }
      function updateLeftRetainedCount() {
        leftRetainedCounter.textContent = leftRetained.length;
      }

      document.getElementById('leftAdd').addEventListener('click', leftAddWidget);
      document.getElementById('leftRemove').addEventListener('click', leftRemoveWidget);

      // ---------------------------
      // Fixed implementation
      // ---------------------------
      var rightNextId = 1;
      var rightVisibleContainer = document.getElementById('rightWidgets');
      var rightVisibleCounter = document.getElementById('rightVisible');
      var rightRetainedCounter = document.getElementById('rightRetained');

      // For the fixed version we will keep a registry of currently-visible widgets
      // When removing, we will actively detach listeners and clear references.
      var rightRegistry = []; // tracks current widgets

      function rightAddWidget() {
        var id = rightNextId++;
        var heavyString = new Array(2000).join('y') + id; // similar heavy payload
        // prepare an object to hold references
        var item = { id: id, heavy: heavyString, node: null, listener: null };

        // create DOM element with a button; we create the listener separately so we can remove it later
        var el = createWidgetElement(id, function () {}); // placeholder
        // create listener separately and attach via addEventListener so we can remove it
        var btn = el.querySelector('button');
        function onAction() {
          // small closure, but references are reachable only while node is in registry
          console.log('Right Widget action', id);
        }
        btn.addEventListener('click', onAction);

        // fill registry entry
        item.node = el;
        item.listener = onAction;

        // put into DOM and registry
        rightVisibleContainer.appendChild(el);
        rightRegistry.push(item);
        updateRightVisibleCount();
        updateRightRetainedCount();
      }

      function rightRemoveWidget() {
        // remove last visible one from DOM and clean references properly
        if (!rightRegistry.length) return;
        var item = rightRegistry.pop(); // take last registry item
        // detach event listener
        var btn = item.node.querySelector('button');
        try {
          btn.removeEventListener('click', item.listener);
        } catch (e) {
          // ignore
        }
        // remove node from DOM
        if (item.node && item.node.parentNode) {
          item.node.parentNode.removeChild(item.node);
        }
        // clear references so GC can collect
        item.node = null;
        item.listener = null;
        item.heavy = null;
        // item goes out of scope now (not referenced by anyone), so can be collected
        updateRightVisibleCount();
        updateRightRetainedCount();
      }

      function updateRightVisibleCount() {
        rightVisibleCounter.textContent = rightVisibleContainer.children.length;
      }
      function updateRightRetainedCount() {
        rightRetainedCounter.textContent = rightRegistry.length;
      }

      document.getElementById('rightAdd').addEventListener('click', rightAddWidget);
      document.getElementById('rightRemove').addEventListener('click', rightRemoveWidget);

      // ---------------------------
      // Extra: periodically show simple retained rough memory indicator
      // ---------------------------
      // This indicator is simplistic: it counts the number of retained objects we intentionally kept.
      // In a real app you'd use the browser's heap profiler / devtools for real memory inspection.
      function refreshStats() {
        updateLeftRetainedCount();
        updateLeftVisibleCount();
        updateRightRetainedCount();
        updateRightVisibleCount();
      }
      setInterval(refreshStats, 500);

      // Pre-populate a few widgets for demo convenience
      for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        leftAddWidget();
        rightAddWidget();
      }

      // Expose some internals to console for inspection if desired
      window.__demo = {
        leftRetained: leftRetained,
        rightRegistry: rightRegistry
      };

    })();
  </script>

  <hr style="margin-top:18px" />
  <div style="margin-top:8px">
    <strong>Why "GC isn't working" is usually the wrong diagnosis</strong>
    <div style="margin-top:6px">
      - The JavaScript garbage collector reclaims objects that are unreachable from roots (global variables, currently executing stack frames, DOM/node roots, closures, etc). If an object remains reachable, GC will not collect it.  
      - Common causes of apparent leaks: arrays/maps that keep references to removed items, failing to call removeEventListener (or using inline handlers kept in other scopes), timers (setInterval/setTimeout), or closures that accidentally capture DOM nodes or large data.  
      - The correct fix is to find the live references and break them (remove listeners, clear arrays, null out properties) so objects become unreachable. Use DevTools memory snapshots (allocation/retainer graphs) to find what is holding objects alive.  
    </div>
  </div>

</body>
</html>

How to use the demo:
- Click "Add widget" on either side to create widgets (each allocates a small heavy string to make retention visible).
- Click "Remove widget" — on the left side the visible DOM nodes are removed but the "Retained references" counter stays high because we intentionally keep objects in leftRetained.
- On the right side, removal detaches listeners and clears references so the retained count drops.
- To investigate real memory, open DevTools → Memory → Take heap snapshots and compare retained objects before/after removals.

If you want, I can:
- Add a heap-snapshot walkthrough for Chrome DevTools with specific steps to identify retained DOM nodes and their retaining paths.
- Modify the demo to demonstrate other common leak sources (timers, closures in global maps, event delegation mistakes).

Below is a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates the scenario you described: a widget dashboard where widgets can be added and removed dynamically. The “buggy” version leaks memory by keeping DOM references and event listeners after widgets are removed. The “fixed” version cleans up event listeners and clears references so the garbage collector can reclaim memory.

Save this to a file (for example, dashboard-leak-demo.html) and open it in a modern browser. Use the controls to add/remove widgets and watch the counters. The page also includes buttons to forcibly allocate a chunk of data per widget to make the leak more obvious in memory profilers.

Explanation (also visible in the page):
- The garbage collector works; a growing memory graph in a dashboard usually indicates live references are still reachable. Event listeners and variables that hold DOM nodes keep those nodes reachable, preventing GC.
- The “buggy” widget implementation attaches event listeners and stores references in a global array without removing them on widget removal — so removed widgets remain reachable via that array and their listeners remain active.
- The “fixed” implementation removes listeners and clears references so the GC can reclaim memory.
- Use the browser's Memory / Heap snapshot tools to confirm: after removing widgets, take a heap snapshot — you should be able to see retained objects caused by the global arrays and closures in the buggy case.

Here is the HTML file:

```html
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8" />
<title>Widget Dashboard: Leaky vs Fixed Demo</title>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" />
<style>
  body { font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", Roboto, "Helvetica Neue", Arial; margin: 20px; color: #222; }
  h1 { margin: 0 0 8px 0; font-size: 20px; }
  .controls { margin: 12px 0; display:flex; gap:8px; align-items:center; flex-wrap:wrap; }
  button { padding:6px 10px; font-size:14px; cursor:pointer; }
  .cols { display:flex; gap:16px; align-items:flex-start; }
  .col { border:1px solid #ddd; padding:12px; border-radius:6px; width:48%; box-sizing:border-box; }
  .widgets { margin-top:8px; display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:8px; }
  .widget { border:1px solid #bbb; padding:8px; border-radius:6px; background:#fafafa; display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; gap:8px; }
  .small { font-size:12px; color:#444 }
  .status { margin-top:8px; font-size:13px; color:#333 }
  .counters { display:flex; gap:12px; margin-top:8px; }
  .counter { background:#f4f4f7; padding:8px; border-radius:6px; border:1px solid #eee; min-width:110px; text-align:center; }
  .danger { color:#a00; font-weight:600; }
  .hint { margin-top:10px; font-size:13px; color:#555; }
  code { background:#f3f3f3; padding:2px 4px; border-radius:4px; }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Widget Dashboard Memory Leak Demo</h1>
<p class="small">Add and remove widgets. One column intentionally leaks references and listeners; the other cleans them up. Use your browser's memory tools for verification.</p>

<div class="controls">
  <label><button id="addLeaky">Add leaky widget</button></label>
  <label><button id="removeLeaky">Remove last leaky widget</button></label>
  <label><button id="addFixed">Add fixed widget</button></label>
  <label><button id="removeFixed">Remove last fixed widget</button></label>
  <label><button id="allocateMemory">Allocate ~1MB per widget (for visibility)</button></label>
  <label><button id="clearAlloc">Clear allocated memory</button></label>
</div>

<div class="counters">
  <div class="counter"><div>Leaky widgets</div><div id="leakyCount" style="font-size:16px; font-weight:700">0</div></div>
  <div class="counter"><div>Fixed widgets</div><div id="fixedCount" style="font-size:16px; font-weight:700">0</div></div>
  <div class="counter"><div>Leaky retained refs</div><div id="leakyRefs" style="font-size:16px; font-weight:700">0</div></div>
</div>

<div class="cols">
  <div class="col" id="leakyCol">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 6px 0">Leaky Dashboard (buggy)</h2>
    <div class="small">This implementation intentionally keeps references and listeners after widget removal.</div>
    <div class="widgets" id="leakyWidgets"></div>
    <div class="status" id="leakyStatus"></div>
  </div>

  <div class="col" id="fixedCol">
    <h2 style="margin:0 0 6px 0">Fixed Dashboard</h2>
    <div class="small">This implementation removes listeners and clears references on removal.</div>
    <div class="widgets" id="fixedWidgets"></div>
    <div class="status" id="fixedStatus"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="hint">
  Explanation highlights:
  <ul>
    <li>The GC only collects objects that are no longer reachable from roots (globals, closures, DOM, event listeners, etc.).</li>
    <li>If you keep a reference to an element or have an active listener with a closure capturing DOM or large data, those objects stay live and won't be reclaimed.</li>
    <li>Use heap snapshots and the retained size / retaining paths to see what keeps objects alive.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<script>
(function(){
  // Simple utilities
  function $(id){ return document.getElementById(id); }

  // Global arrays to simulate accidental retention
  // BUGGY: keeps strong references to removed widget objects and their elements/listeners
  const leakyRegistry = [];

  // For demonstration we allow allocating some big arrays per widget to amplify memory usage
  const perWidgetAllocation = new Map(); // Map<id, ArrayBuffer>

  // Counters and DOM references
  let leakyId = 0;
  let fixedId = 0;

  const leakyWidgetsRoot = $('leakyWidgets');
  const fixedWidgetsRoot = $('fixedWidgets');
  const leakyCountEl = $('leakyCount');
  const fixedCountEl = $('fixedCount');
  const leakyRefsEl = $('leakyRefs');
  const leakyStatus = $('leakyStatus');
  const fixedStatus = $('fixedStatus');

  function updateCounters(){
    leakyCountEl.textContent = leakyWidgetsRoot.children.length;
    fixedCountEl.textContent = fixedWidgetsRoot.children.length;
    leakyRefsEl.textContent = leakyRegistry.length;
  }

  // ---------- BUGGY: leaky widget implementation ----------
  function createLeakyWidget() {
    leakyId++;
    const id = 'leaky-' + leakyId;

    // Create DOM for widget
    const el = document.createElement('div');
    el.className = 'widget';
    el.id = id;
    el.innerHTML = '<div>Leaky widget #' + leakyId + '</div>';

    // A button inside widget that uses a closure capturing `el`
    const btn = document.createElement('button');
    btn.textContent = 'Click me';
    el.appendChild(btn);

    // Some per-widget state object (could be larger)
    const state = { id, createdAt: Date.now(), element: el };

    // Event listener that forms a closure capturing `state` (and thus `el`)
    function onClick() {
      // Access state -> keeps reference alive
      console.log('Leaky widget clicked', state.id);
      // A trivial modification to demonstrate functionality
      el.style.background = '#fffbe6';
      setTimeout(() => el.style.background = '#fafafa', 300);
    }
    btn.addEventListener('click', onClick);

    // BUG: store references in a global registry and never remove them.
    // This simulates a common leak: storing DOM nodes / closures in long-lived arrays.
    leakyRegistry.push({ id, el, btn, onClick, state });

    leakyWidgetsRoot.appendChild(el);
    updateCounters();
    leakyStatus.textContent = 'Leaky registry grows and is never pruned on removal.';
    return id;
  }

  function removeLeakyWidget() {
    // Remove from DOM but the global registry still references it.
    const children = leakyWidgetsRoot.children;
    if (!children.length) return;
    const last = children[children.length - 1];
    last.remove(); // DOM node removed from document
    // BUG: we do not remove corresponding entry from leakyRegistry -> memory leak
    updateCounters();
  }

  // ---------- FIXED: proper cleanup ----------
  // We'll keep a local map of active widget cleanup callbacks
  const fixedCleanup = new Map(); // Map<id, cleanupFn>

  function createFixedWidget() {
    fixedId++;
    const id = 'fixed-' + fixedId;

    const el = document.createElement('div');
    el.className = 'widget';
    el.id = id;
    el.innerHTML = '<div>Fixed widget #' + fixedId + '</div>';

    const btn = document.createElement('button');
    btn.textContent = 'Click me';
    el.appendChild(btn);

    // Some per-widget state object
    const state = { id, createdAt: Date.now() };

    function onClick() {
      console.log('Fixed widget clicked', state.id);
      el.style.background = '#e6ffed';
      setTimeout(() => el.style.background = '#fafafa', 300);
    }
    // Attach listener
    btn.addEventListener('click', onClick);

    // Append to DOM
    fixedWidgetsRoot.appendChild(el);

    // Register cleanup function that will remove listeners and null references
    function cleanup() {
      try {
        btn.removeEventListener('click', onClick);
      } catch (e) {
        // ignore
      }
      // Remove DOM references (if any references to el exist here, clear them)
      // No global array holds this `el` so after cleanup and DOM removal it becomes unreachable.
    }
    fixedCleanup.set(id, cleanup);

    updateCounters();
    fixedStatus.textContent = 'Fixed widgets remove listeners and clear references on removal.';
    return id;
  }

  function removeFixedWidget() {
    const children = fixedWidgetsRoot.children;
    if (!children.length) return;
    const last = children[children.length - 1];
    const id = last.id;
    // Run cleanup
    const cleanup = fixedCleanup.get(id);
    if (cleanup) {
      cleanup();
      fixedCleanup.delete(id);
    }
    // Remove from DOM; after cleanup there should be no remaining references from our code
    last.remove();
    updateCounters();
  }

  // ---------- Memory amplification helpers ----------
  // Allocate roughly 1MB (ArrayBuffer) per widget id to make leak visible in devtools
  function allocatePerWidget() {
    // For each widget in leakyRegistry allocate a chunk if not already allocated
    for (const entry of leakyRegistry) {
      if (!perWidgetAllocation.has(entry.id)) {
        // allocate ~1MB
        perWidgetAllocation.set(entry.id, new ArrayBuffer(1024 * 1024));
      }
    }
    // For fixed widgets allocate similarly but store in a transient Map keyed by DOM id
    for (const el of fixedWidgetsRoot.children) {
      const fid = el.id;
      if (!perWidgetAllocation.has(fid)) {
        perWidgetAllocation.set(fid, new ArrayBuffer(1024 * 1024));
      }
    }
    updatePerWidgetAllocCount();
  }

  function clearAllocations() {
    perWidgetAllocation.clear();
    updatePerWidgetAllocCount();
  }

  function updatePerWidgetAllocCount() {
    // show status briefly
    leakyStatus.textContent = '[Allocations] perWidgetAllocation size: ' + perWidgetAllocation.size;
    fixedStatus.textContent = '[Allocations] perWidgetAllocation size: ' + perWidgetAllocation.size;
    setTimeout(() => {
      leakyStatus.textContent = 'Leaky registry grows and is never pruned on removal.';
      fixedStatus.textContent = 'Fixed widgets remove listeners and clear references on removal.';
    }, 2000);
  }

  // ---------- Wire UI ----------
  $('addLeaky').addEventListener('click', createLeakyWidget);
  $('removeLeaky').addEventListener('click', removeLeakyWidget);
  $('addFixed').addEventListener('click', createFixedWidget);
  $('removeFixed').addEventListener('click', removeFixedWidget);
  $('allocateMemory').addEventListener('click', allocatePerWidget);
  $('clearAlloc').addEventListener('click', clearAllocations);

  // For demonstration, also expose a function to forcibly remove registry entries:
  // This is not wired to UI but shows how to fix the leakyRegistry if desired.
  window.pruneLeakyRegistry = function pruneLeakyRegistry() {
    // Remove entries whose DOM nodes are no longer connected to document
    let kept = 0;
    for (let i = leakyRegistry.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
      const entry = leakyRegistry[i];
      if (!document.body.contains(entry.el)) {
        // Optionally remove listener references too
        try { entry.btn.removeEventListener('click', entry.onClick); } catch(e){}
        leakyRegistry.splice(i, 1);
      } else {
        kept++;
      }
    }
    updateCounters();
    return kept;
  };

  // Auto-update counters periodically
  setInterval(updateCounters, 500);

  // Quick instructions in console for power users
  console.log('Widget leak demo loaded.');
  console.log('Use heap snapshots in DevTools to inspect retained DOM nodes and closures.');
  console.log('You can call pruneLeakyRegistry() from console to simulate a fix for the leaky registry.');
  console.log('Remove widgets from the leaky column, then inspect leakyRegistry in console to see entries still referenced.');
})();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

How to observe the problem in DevTools
- Open the page in Chrome/Edge (or Firefox) and open DevTools → Memory.
- Add several leaky widgets, click "Allocate ~1MB per widget" to inflate memory allocations (this makes the leaked retained size more visible).
- Remove those leaky widgets from the dashboard (they disappear visually).
- Take a heap snapshot. Look for objects referencing DOM nodes from the leaky column — you should see the entries in the global leakyRegistry retaining the nodes and their closures.
- In the fixed column, after removal the DOM nodes and listener closures should not appear in retained paths (unless something else references them).

Why the colleague's "GC not working" diagnosis is likely wrong
- The garbage collector only reclaims objects that are unreachable from roots. If memory usage grows, something is still holding references. Common culprits: global arrays, closures (e.g., event listeners that reference DOM/state), timers, or other long-lived caches.
- Removing an element from the DOM doesn't automatically free memory if your JS still holds references to that element (or a closure that captures it). Browsers implement GC correctly; most observed “leaks” are due to reachable objects kept by application code.

If you'd like, I can:
- Modify the demo to add automatic heap snapshots and show retained sizes.
- Add a version that leaks via setInterval timers (another common pattern).
- Provide step-by-step DevTools instructions tailored to your browser.

Below is a single self-contained HTML file you can save and open in a browser. It creates a simple "dashboard" that can add and remove widgets. There are two panes:

- "Leaking version" — when widgets are removed they leave behind event listeners and closures that keep DOM nodes and data reachable, so memory usage grows.
- "Fixed version" — the same logic but it explicitly removes listeners and clears references when a widget is removed, allowing the garbage collector to reclaim memory.

The page also shows a "widget tracker" counter that increments when a widget is created and decrements when the widget is properly cleaned up. In the leaking version the counter does not decrement correctly (because cleanup wasn't done), so you can see the mismatch between the number of visible widget elements and the tracked alive objects. This demonstrates that the issue is about lingering references (code-level leaks), not a bug in the GC itself.

Save the text below as a file named e.g. dashboard-memory-demo.html and open it in Chrome/Firefox. Use the add/remove buttons many times and watch the counters. Open the browser devtools Memory/Performance tabs to inspect retained objects if you like.

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8"/>
<title>Widget Dashboard — Memory Leak Demo</title>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"/>
<style>
  body { font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", Roboto, Arial; margin: 16px; color: #111; }
  h1 { margin: 0 0 12px 0; font-size: 20px; }
  .container { display: flex; gap: 16px; align-items: flex-start; }
  .panel { border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; width: 48%; box-sizing: border-box; border-radius: 6px; background: #f9f9f9; }
  .controls { display: flex; gap: 8px; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .widgets { border-top: 1px dashed #ccc; padding-top: 8px; }
  .widget { background: white; border: 1px solid #e0e0e0; padding: 8px; margin: 8px 0; border-radius: 4px; display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; }
  button { cursor: pointer; }
