  code { background:#eee; padding:2px 4px; border-radius:4px; }
</style>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Widget Dashboard Memory Leak Demonstration</h1>
<p>Two side-by-side dashboards. The left intentionally leaks by keeping references and listeners after removal. The right cleans up properly. Use the buttons to add/remove widgets repeatedly and watch the counters.</p>

<div class="container">
  <div class="panel" id="leak-panel">
    <h2>Leaking version</h2>
    <div class="controls">
      <button id="leak-add">Add widget</button>
      <button id="leak-remove">Remove last widget</button>
    </div>
    <div class="stats">
      Visible widgets: <span id="leak-visible">0</span> • Tracked alive objects: <span id="leak-tracked">0</span>
    </div>
    <div class="widgets" id="leak-widgets"></div>
    <div class="note">
      This version attaches listeners and stores references on a global "leakedStore" and never removes them. The GC is not "broken" — it's the code keeping things reachable.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="panel" id="fixed-panel">
    <h2>Fixed version</h2>
    <div class="controls">
      <button id="fixed-add">Add widget</button>
      <button id="fixed-remove">Remove last widget</button>
    </div>
    <div class="stats">
      Visible widgets: <span id="fixed-visible">0</span> • Tracked alive objects: <span id="fixed-tracked">0</span>
    </div>
    <div class="widgets" id="fixed-widgets"></div>
    <div class="note">
      This version removes listeners and clears references when widgets are removed so the GC can reclaim memory.
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
/*
Overview:
- This demo creates lightweight "widget" DOM nodes that also capture some data in closures.
- The leaking version intentionally keeps references to DOM nodes and closures in a global store,
  and attaches event listeners without removing them — preventing garbage collection.
- The fixed version removes listeners and clears references, allowing the GC to reclaim memory.

How to experiment:
- Add a bunch of widgets (e.g. 500+), then remove them.
- The "visible widgets" shows current DOM elements.
- The "tracked alive objects" shows how many widget objects our code considers "alive".
  In the leaking version this number will not go down when widgets are removed.
- Use browser devtools -> Memory to take heap snapshots if you want to inspect retained nodes.
*/

// Utility for IDs
let idCounter = 1;
function nextId() { return idCounter++; }

// -----------------------
// Leaking version
// -----------------------
const leakWidgetsRoot = document.getElementById('leak-widgets');
const leakVisibleEl = document.getElementById('leak-visible');
const leakTrackedEl = document.getElementById('leak-tracked');

// Intentionally leaked store: keeps references to closures and DOM nodes
const leakedStore = { items: [] };
// Tracked count only updated by our code (illustrative)
let leakTrackedCount = 0;

function createLeakingWidget() {
  const id = nextId();
  // create a DOM node
  const el = document.createElement('div');
  el.className = 'widget';
  el.innerHTML = '<div>Widget #' + id + '</div><div><button class="leak-action">Action</button></div>';

  // create some captured data to mimic real widget state (array of strings)
  const bigData = new Array(2000).fill('x' + id); // relatively large to make retention visible

  // attach an event listener that captures the DOM node and bigData in closure
  function onAction() {
    // do something trivial but capture 'el' and 'bigData'
    console.log('Leaky widget', id, 'action, data length:', bigData.length);
    // access el to make sure it's captured
    el.style.background = el.style.background ? '' : '#fff8e0';
  }
  const btn = el.querySelector('.leak-action');
  btn.addEventListener('click', onAction);

  // Intentionally store references in the leakedStore so they never get freed
  leakedStore.items.push({ id, el, onAction, bigData });

  leakTrackedCount++;
  leakTrackedEl.textContent = String(leakTrackedCount);

  return el;
}

function removeLastLeakingWidget() {
  // remove from DOM
  const last = leakWidgetsRoot.lastElementChild;
  if (!last) return;
  leakWidgetsRoot.removeChild(last);

  // Intentionally do NOT remove the entry from leakedStore.
  // Therefore the stored {el, bigData, onAction} remains reachable and cannot be GC'd.

  // visible count changes but tracked count stays unchanged to illustrate leak
  leakVisibleEl.textContent = String(leakWidgetsRoot.children.length);
  // tracked intentionally not decremented
  leakTrackedEl.textContent = String(leakTrackedCount);
}

// Buttons wiring
document.getElementById('leak-add').addEventListener('click', function addMany() {
  // Add 20 at a time to make the effect faster to observe
  for (let i=0;i<20;i++) {
    const w = createLeakingWidget();
    leakWidgetsRoot.appendChild(w);
  }
  leakVisibleEl.textContent = String(leakWidgetsRoot.children.length);
});
document.getElementById('leak-remove').addEventListener('click', function() {
  // remove 20 at a time
  for (let i=0;i<20;i++) removeLastLeakingWidget();
  leakVisibleEl.textContent = String(leakWidgetsRoot.children.length);
});

// -----------------------
// Fixed version
// -----------------------
const fixedWidgetsRoot = document.getElementById('fixed-widgets');
const fixedVisibleEl = document.getElementById('fixed-visible');
const fixedTrackedEl = document.getElementById('fixed-tracked');

let fixedTrackedCount = 0;

// We'll keep a store of active widgets so we can cleanly teardown each
const activeFixedWidgets = new Map();

function createFixedWidget() {
  const id = nextId();
  const el = document.createElement('div');
  el.className = 'widget';
  el.innerHTML = '<div>Widget #' + id + '</div><div><button class="fixed-action">Action</button></div>';

  // mimic some large per-widget state
  const bigData = new Array(2000).fill('y' + id);

  function onAction() {
    console.log('Fixed widget', id, 'action, data length:', bigData.length);
    el.style.background = el.style.background ? '' : '#e8fff2';
  }
  const btn = el.querySelector('.fixed-action');
  btn.addEventListener('click', onAction);

  // store what we need to teardown later
  activeFixedWidgets.set(id, { id, el, onAction, bigData, btn });

  fixedTrackedCount++;
  fixedTrackedEl.textContent = String(fixedTrackedCount);

  return { id, el };
}

function removeLastFixedWidget() {
  // remove from DOM
  const last = fixedWidgetsRoot.lastElementChild;
  if (!last) return;

  // find its id by parsing text (in a real app you'd store id on element.dataset)
  const label = last.textContent || '';
  const m = label.match(/#(\d+)/);
  const id = m ? Number(m[1]) : null;

  fixedWidgetsRoot.removeChild(last);

  if (id && activeFixedWidgets.has(id)) {
    // Proper cleanup:
    const info = activeFixedWidgets.get(id);
    // remove event listener
    info.btn.removeEventListener('click', info.onAction);
    // clear large arrays and references
    info.bigData = null;
    info.onAction = null;
    info.btn = null;
    // remove from map so nothing keeps a reference to el or bigData
    activeFixedWidgets.delete(id);

    fixedTrackedCount--;
    fixedTrackedEl.textContent = String(fixedTrackedCount);
  }

  fixedVisibleEl.textContent = String(fixedWidgetsRoot.children.length);
}

// Buttons wiring
document.getElementById('fixed-add').addEventListener('click', function() {
  for (let i=0;i<20;i++) {
    const { id, el } = createFixedWidget();
    fixedWidgetsRoot.appendChild(el);
  }
  fixedVisibleEl.textContent = String(fixedWidgetsRoot.children.length);
});
document.getElementById('fixed-remove').addEventListener('click', function() {
  for (let i=0;i<20;i++) removeLastFixedWidget();
  fixedVisibleEl.textContent = String(fixedWidgetsRoot.children.length);
});

// initialize counts
leakVisibleEl.textContent = '0';
leakTrackedEl.textContent = '0';
fixedVisibleEl.textContent = '0';
fixedTrackedEl.textContent = '0';

/*
Why this demonstrates that the GC isn't to blame:
- The garbage collector only reclaims objects that are unreachable from roots (global objects, closures
  still referenced by other live objects, active stack frames, etc.).
- In the leaking version we intentionally keep references to removed DOM nodes and large arrays inside 'leakedStore'.
  As long as 'leakedStore.items' contains those entries, they remain reachable, so GC will not free them.
- In other words: memory growth is caused by application code holding references, not a faulty GC.
- The fixed version removes event listeners and deletes references, making those objects unreachable and therefore
  collectible.

Notes for real debugging:
- Use heap snapshots in the browser devtools to find detached DOM nodes or objects retaining large arrays.
- Look for event listeners, closures, timers, or global caches that keep references.
- Tools: Chrome DevTools -> Memory -> take snapshot; filter for 'Detached' elements or inspect the retaining paths.
*/
</script>
</body>
</html>

Explanation summary:
- The leak is produced by storing references (DOM nodes, closure data and listeners) in a long-lived object (leakedStore) and not removing them when widgets are removed from the DOM.
- The garbage collector functions correctly: it won't free objects that are still reachable. The fix is to remove listeners and clear references when widgets are torn down (as shown in the Fixed version).

Below is a single, self-contained HTML file you can save and open in a browser. It implements a small “dashboard” where you can add/remove widgets. It contains two columns:

- "Leaky version" — intentionally creates a memory leak by attaching event listeners and storing references on a global map that are never cleared when a widget is removed.
- "Fixed version" — removes listeners and clears references when a widget is removed.

Each widget has a per-widget counter that increments on an interval. A global "simulated profiler" (simple counters shown in the UI) tracks the number of active timer callbacks and number of stored references; those numbers grow in the leaky version when you add and remove widgets repeatedly, demonstrating why memory usage increases. At the end I explain why blaming the GC is usually incorrect here.

